            },
            "answerKey": {
              "assessmentType": "multiplechoice",
              "answers": {
                "answer_3": {
                  "score": 0.0,
                  "response": "Levittown symbolized the most significant social trend of the postwar era in the United States—the flight to the suburbs. These residential areas surrounding cities such as New York and Chicago nearly doubled in the 1950s. Suburban life depended on the automobile and was made possible by America’s new highways and expressways that allowed fathers to commute to jobs in the cities, often an hour or more away."
